notes[4]{created_at,author,text}:
  "2026-05-11T17:40:34.750Z",codex-agent,"Pi package research snapshot 2026-05-11: pi.dev/packages advertises npm-published package catalog entries and installs with pi install npm:<package>. Current Pi docs define packages as bundles of extensions, skills, prompt templates, and themes; package.json pi manifest supports extensions/skills/prompts/themes arrays plus gallery image/video; conventional directories are auto-discovered if no pi manifest exists. Sources include npm, git URLs/shorthands, and local paths; project-local installs use -l and persist to .pi/settings.json; temporary try-run uses -e. Pi package manager dedupes project over global, supports filtering per resource type, pins versioned npm/git refs, runs npm install for npm/git packages, and loads resources through a central resource-loader."
  "2026-05-11T19:49:18.511Z",codex-agent,"External research refresh 2026-05-11: Pi packages bundle extensions, skills, prompts, and themes; support npm/git/local sources; run npm install for npm/git packages; use package.json pi manifests or convention directories; support per-resource filters, project-over-global dedupe, enable/disable controls, and explicit security warnings. OpenClaw separates small core from npm/community plugins, supports local/archive/npm/marketplace installs, list/inspect/doctor/enable/disable, discovery precedence, plugin slots, manifest-declared capabilities, and focused SDK subpath imports. Implication for pm: keep item/storage/history/config/output/package loader primitives in core; move optional workflows/resources/integrations behind installable packages with manifest contracts and diagnostics."
  "2026-05-11T21:39:51.332Z",codex-agent,"Reference architecture distilled for pm: small core keeps project-management primitives, storage, history, config, contracts, output, telemetry, and package loader; optional custom workflows ship as npm/git/local packages with manifests, managed state, diagnostics, enable/disable, and upgrade paths. Pi/OpenClaw are references only; no agent-harness semantics belong in pm core."
  "2026-05-14T05:43:35.876Z",codex-agent,"Detailed package extraction plan from 2026-05-14 codebase audit: 1) pm-calendar: move calendar/cal views, reminders/events/recurrence expansion, and schedule presets behind package commands while keeping item deadline fields core. 2) pm-search-advanced: keep keyword search core, move semantic/hybrid reindex, embedding providers, vector stores, cache refresh, and advanced search provider defaults to installable search packages. 3) pm-linked-test-runner: keep linked test metadata core, move subprocess execution, background runs, assertion policies, PM-context sandboxing, and test-runs lifecycle to a runner package. 4) pm-governance-audit: move dedupe-audit, comments-audit, normalize sweeps, advanced validate checks, and broad update-many governance workflows to a governance package. 5) pm-guide-shell: keep help core, move guide topics, completion generation, and shell-specific UX to a docs/shell package. 6) pm-templates: move templates save/list/show and create --template acceleration into a templates package. Cross-cutting requirement: every extraction must preserve SDK primitives, dynamic contracts/MCP availability, package TypeScript sources, temp-project dogfood, and release/observability gates."
files[1]{path,scope,note}:
  src/cli/commands/index.ts,project,pruned package-owned command exports from core barrel
body: "Package-first architecture plan after external package-manager references:\\n\\n1. Keep bare pm core limited to project-management primitives: item storage/format, history, locking, settings, output, command runtime, lifecycle commands, SDK contracts, package loading, governance, and minimal health.\\n2. Treat workflow-specific behavior as optional packages unless it is required to manage pm items without packages. First delivered slice: pm-hxp2 extracted Beads/Todos import/export bridges into installable first-party package roots.\\n3. Keep follow-up package work provider-neutral and pm-specific: pm-t5ud for manifest/package contract design, pm-su6i for pm package resource loading, pm-lwun for package-first docs/UX terminology, and pm-2b3l for package gallery metadata.\\n4. Later package-boundary candidates include templates, search providers/vector stores, calendar presentations, telemetry/Sentry adapters, and external bridge workflows after their core contracts are narrowed.\\n5. Verification protocol for each slice: sandboxed PM_PATH/PM_GLOBAL_PATH tests, temp-project pm install dogfood, contracts/health/package doctor, full coverage, observability checks, commit/push, and green GitHub Actions."
